body:
Summary of bugs in the capture pipeline
🐞 Bug 1 — DirectImageCapture.Stop() disposes resources before stopping the consumer thread
File: Capture/DirectImageCapture.cs, lines 1001–1009
csharppublic override async Task Stop()
{
    if (!WasStarted)
        return;

    DisposeInternal();   // ❌ disposes Device, BackingTexture, StagingTexture, DuplicatedOutput
    await base.Stop();   // THEN stops the consumer thread that might still be using them
}
Why it's wrong: base.Stop() is what calls BlockingCollection.CompleteAdding() and awaits the consumer _task. That task is still running Save(BlockingCollection.Take()) — which on DirectX captures touches GPU resources like StagingTexture (via Device.ImmediateContext.MapSubresource, etc.). Disposing the Device and staging textures before waiting for the consumer to finish draining the queue causes null‑ref / disposed‑object exceptions at the end of a DirectX recording.
Fix: Swap the order.
csharppublic override async Task Stop()
{
    if (!WasStarted)
        return;

    await base.Stop();   // drain the consumer first
    DisposeInternal();   // then free the GPU resources
}
The same flipped order almost certainly exists in DirectCachedCapture.cs, DirectChangedImageCapture.cs, and DirectChangedCachedCapture.cs — worth grepping them and applying the same swap.

🐞 Bug 2 — BaseCapture swallows every exception from the producer/consumer loop except the first one
File: Capture/BaseCapture.cs, lines 97–112
csharp_task = Task.Factory.StartNew(() =>
{
    try
    {
        while (true)
            Save(BlockingCollection.Take());
    }
    catch (InvalidOperationException) { ... }
    catch (Exception e)
    {
        Application.Current.Dispatcher.Invoke(() => OnError?.Invoke(e));
    }
});
Why it's wrong: a single catch (Exception) around while (true) { Save(...) } means the first frame‑save error kills the consumer thread for the whole recording. From that point on, frames pile up in BlockingCollection forever, memory grows, and the user doesn't know because OnError fires once and quietly stops the pipeline. The loop should continue on transient save errors, only breaking on real terminal conditions.
Fix:
csharpwhile (true)
{
    try { Save(BlockingCollection.Take()); }
    catch (InvalidOperationException) { return; } // CompleteAdding → exit
    catch (Exception e)
    {
        Application.Current.Dispatcher.Invoke(() => OnError?.Invoke(e));
        // keep going — one bad frame shouldn't kill the recording
    }
}

🐞 Bug 3 — ImageCapture.Capture() / CaptureWithCursor() leaks GDI bitmap handles on every frame
File: Capture/ImageCapture.cs, lines 55–80 and 87–163
csharpframe.Image = Image.FromHbitmap(CompatibleBitmap);
Image.FromHbitmap creates a managed copy of the HBITMAP — but because the underlying CompatibleBitmap is reused every frame (it's the class field selected into CompatibleDeviceContext), the actual problem is different: Save() does frame.Image.Dispose() eventually, but if the producer exception swallow from Bug 2 kills the consumer thread, those Image objects never get disposed and the GDI handle count climbs until Windows rejects new bitmaps (Parameter is not valid / A generic error occurred in GDI+). The empty catch (Exception) at line 74 hides this entirely. Related: the commented‑out LogWriter.Log(ex, ...) calls throughout these files (lines 76, 159, and many more) — exceptions are silently swallowed rather than logged, so users have no diagnostics when capture fails.
Fix: re‑enable the LogWriter.Log calls. It's a one‑character edit per site and dramatically improves debuggability.

🐞 Bug 4 — CachedCapture.Stop() can throw NullReferenceException if Start() partially failed
File: Capture/CachedCapture.cs, lines 200–217
csharppublic override async Task Stop()
{
    if (!WasStarted)
        return;
    await base.Stop();

    await _compressStream.DisposeAsync();   // ❌ may be null
    await _bufferedStream.FlushAsync();
    await _fileStream.FlushAsync();
    ...
}
Why it's wrong: Start() (line 50–52) opens three streams in sequence. If new FileStream(...) succeeds but new BufferedStream(...) or new DeflateStream(...) throws (e.g. out‑of‑memory with a very large MemoryCacheSize setting), some of the stream fields are assigned and some aren't, but WasStarted is already true because base.Start() set it. Stop() will then NRE on the null stream — and because FileStream is never closed, the cache file stays locked until the process exits, blocking subsequent recordings.
Fix: wrap stream creation in try/catch in Start() to roll back on failure, and null‑check in Stop():
csharpif (_compressStream != null) await _compressStream.DisposeAsync();
if (_bufferedStream != null) { await _bufferedStream.FlushAsync(); await _bufferedStream.DisposeAsync(); }
if (_fileStream    != null) { await _fileStream.FlushAsync();    await _fileStream.DisposeAsync();    }

🐞 Bug 5 — ImageCapture.CaptureWithCursor() double‑deletes the cursor handle
File: Capture/ImageCapture.cs, lines 131–138 (and the identical code in CachedCapture.cs lines 136–143)
csharpGdi32.DeleteObject(iconInfo.hbmColor);
Gdi32.DeleteObject(iconInfo.hbmMask);
...
User32.DestroyIcon(hicon);
...
Gdi32.DeleteObject(cursorInfo.hCursor);   // ❌ WRONG
Why it's wrong:

cursorInfo.hCursor is a cursor handle, not a GDI object. Gdi32.DeleteObject on it is invalid — the Win32 docs explicitly say "Do not use this function on cursors or icons" — and on some systems leaks the handle / on others silently fails.
Worse: hicon was created via User32.CopyIcon(cursorInfo.hCursor). The original cursorInfo.hCursor is owned by the system and must never be destroyed by the caller; only the copy (hicon) should be destroyed (already done correctly with DestroyIcon(hicon)).

Fix: Delete line 138 in ImageCapture.cs and line 143 in CachedCapture.cs entirely. The DestroyIcon(hicon) call is correct and sufficient.

🐞 Bug 6 — Frame numbering race between capture callback and IsAcceptingFrames
File: Capture/ImageCapture.cs and CachedCapture.cs
csharpFrameCount++;
frame.Path = $"{Project.FullPath}{FrameCount}.png";
...
if (IsAcceptingFrames)
    BlockingCollection.Add(frame);
Why it's wrong: FrameCount is incremented before the IsAcceptingFrames check. If Stop() is called mid‑capture, IsAcceptingFrames flips to false, the frame is discarded — but FrameCount has already advanced. The next captured frame (if any) will reuse the same incremented number, but more importantly, Project.Frames.Count and FrameCount drift out of sync, which matters for features that rely on sequential numbering of PNG files on disk.
Fix: only increment FrameCount after confirming the frame is being added:
csharpif (!IsAcceptingFrames)
    return FrameCount;

FrameCount++;
frame.Path = $"{Project.FullPath}{FrameCount}.png";
...
BlockingCollection.Add(frame);

🐞 Bug 7 — BaseCapture.DisposeInternal() calls _task.Dispose() without guaranteeing the task has reached a terminal state
File: Capture/BaseCapture.cs, lines 170–180
csharpprivate async Task DisposeInternal()
{
    if (WasStarted)
        await Stop();

    _task?.Dispose();   // ❌ throws if _task isn't RanToCompletion/Faulted/Canceled
    _task = null;

    BlockingCollection?.Dispose();
    BlockingCollection = null;
}
Why it's wrong: Task.Dispose() is one of the few BCL Dispose() methods that actively throws — if the task is in any state other than RanToCompletion, Faulted, or Canceled, it raises InvalidOperationException with the message "A task may only be disposed if it is in a completion state." This is exactly the error the user originally reported.
The trigger path is capture-swapping in Recorder.PrepareCapture(). When the user switches the recording mode to DirectX, the recorder instantiates a new capture object and calls DisposeAsync() on the existing one. That existing capture's consumer task — the long-running background loop started in BaseCapture.Start() — only completes when BlockingCollection.CompleteAdding() signals it. Because DisposeInternal() only calls Stop() (which does the CompleteAdding + await) when WasStarted is true, there are paths where the task is still in WaitingForActivation or Running when Dispose() is hit. That's when the throw happens, and the user sees the dialog.
Compounding this: Task.Dispose() is almost never necessary in modern .NET. Microsoft's own guidance recommends against calling it — the only thing it releases is an internal WaitHandle that may not even have been allocated, and the GC cleans the task up regardless.
Fix:

Remove the _task.Dispose() call entirely — that alone stops the throw.
As a safety net, if _task is still running when we reach disposal (because Stop() was skipped), call BlockingCollection.CompleteAdding() and await _task ourselves, wrapped in a try/catch that swallows any fault (faults are already surfaced via OnError inside the consumer loop). This prevents leaking a running background loop that would otherwise outlive the capture object.

csharpprivate async Task DisposeInternal()
{
    if (WasStarted)
        await Stop();

    if (_task != null)
    {
        try
        {
            if (!_task.IsCompleted)
            {
                BlockingCollection?.CompleteAdding();
                await _task;
            }
        }
        catch { /* already surfaced via OnError in Start() */ }

        _task = null;
    }

    BlockingCollection?.Dispose();
    BlockingCollection = null;
}

